@vivsriaus, it is great to see the new API to get the `built-in-policies`! Here are my 2 cents to consolidate the code:
1. Can we remove the `supported_api_version` which fuzzes the main logics here? The upstream method is already scoped under the api-version condition in the commands.py, so I don't believe this check is ever needed. You can use code comments if there are something important you like to communicate
2. Reuse the same `try-catch` block for both policy definition and definition set.

I would imaging the code would look like:
```python
def _get_custom_or_builtin_policy(client, name, for_policy_set=False):
    from msrest.exceptions import HttpOperationError
    op_groups = client.policy_set_definitions if for_policy_set else client.policy_definitions
    try:
        return op_groups.get(name)
    except (CloudError, HttpOperationError) as ex:
        status_code = ex.status_code if isinstance(ex, CloudError) else ex.response.status_code
        if status_code == 404:
            return op_groups.get_built_in(name)
        raise
```
One question here though, why  `policy_set_definitions` doesn't raise regular `CloudError`, rather its own model error type?

